{{Infobox religious building | name = Gyobutsuji Zen Monastery | native_name = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = Country Road 9, [[Kingston, Madison County, Arkansas|Kingston]] [[Arkansas]], 72742 | coordinates = | religious_affiliation = [[Sōtō]] [[Zen]], [[Kodo Sawaki|Sawaki Lineage]] | deity = | country = United States | functional_status = | website = http://www.gyobutsuji.org | founded_by = [[Shoryu Bradley]] | year_completed = 2011 }}
{{nihongo|'''Gyobutsuji Zen Monastery'''|行仏寺|gyōbutsu-ji}} is a small [[Sōtō]] [[Zen]] [[Buddhist]] [[monastery]] near [[Kingston, Madison County, Arkansas|Kingston]] in [[Madison County, Arkansas|Madison County]], [[Arkansas]] in the [[United States]]. It is located in the [[Boston Mountains]] of the [[Ozarks]]. The temple focuses primarily on the practice of [[zazen]] in the tradition of [[Kosho Uchiyama]] and [[Shohaku Okumura]], the latter being the teacher of the founder, [[Shōryū Bradley]]. Study of the writings of [[Eihei Dōgen]] and the teachings of [[Shakyamuni Buddha]] are also emphasized. The monastery holds a five-day [[sesshin]] every month except in January and August.<ref name=sotonet>{{Citation| title = Gyobutsuji| publisher = Sotoshu Shumucho| date =| year =| url = http://global.sotozen-net.or.jp/eng/temples/outside_jp/America/048.html| accessdate = 2014-06-21}}</ref>
The name Gyōbutsu-ji literally means 'Practice Buddha Temple' and is derived from [[Eihei Dōgen]]'s [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]] the [[Shōbōgenzō]], specifically the chapter titled [[Gyōbutsu igi]] (行仏威儀).<ref name=sotonet/> While the standard [[Classical Chinese]] interpretation of this title is "practice Buddha's dignified actions", Dōgen re-interpreted it as "dignified actions of the Practice Buddha" in line with his assertion that [[Bhavana|practice]] and [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]] are the same. The chapter explains:
{{quote|text=All buddhas without exception fully practice dignified conduct: this [practice] is Practice Buddha. ... Sharing one corner of the Buddha's dignified conduct is done together with the entire universe, the great earth, and with the entire coming-and-going of life-and-death. ... This is nothing other than the dignified conduct of the oneness of Practice and Buddha.}}
