[[Category:Jainism and other religions]]
[[Category:Hinduism and other religions]]

'''Kakinomoto Shrine''' (柿本神社 ''Kakinomoto-jinja'') is a [[Shinto Shrine]] in [[Akashi, Hyōgo]]. It is also referred to as '''Hitomaru-san'''.

The shrine's principal deity is [[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]], a historical figure who is reputed to have passed through the Akashi area during his life, and who was deified in the centuries following his death, as a god of literature, scholarship, fire safety and childbirth.

According to tradition, the shrine was founded in 887 by the monk [[Kakushō]], in the grounds of the [[Gesshō-ji]] temple. It moved to its current location to accommodate the construction of [[Akashi Castle]].

== Enshrined deities ==
The shrine's principal deity is [[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]],{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} a god of ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' poetry{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} and, by extension, [[scholarship]] and [[literature]],{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} but also, by way of a pair of puns on his name, [[fire safety]] (火止まる ''hi-tomaru'' = "fire stop"){{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} and [[childbirth]] (人生る ''hito-umaru'' = "person is born"){{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}

According to tradition, Hitomaro passed through the Akashi area multiple times while travelling between his home in [[Yamato Province]] and his assigned district in [[Iwami Province]],{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}<!-- Source doesn't explicitly mention "Iwami" but the Hitomaro article's sources do. --> and a poem he wrote on [[Akashi Strait]] survives.{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}

== History ==
The history of the shrine is said to begin in 887 ([[Ninna|Ninna 3]]),{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} when [[Kakushō]] (覚証), a [[Buddhist monk]] of the temple {{illm|Gesshō-ji|ja|月照寺 (明石市)}},{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} speculated that Hitomaro's spirit had come to rest in Akashi{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} and constructed a small shrine at the back of his temple.{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} Both the temple and the shrine were moved to their current location to accommodate the construction of [[Akashi Castle]].{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} In 1723 ([[Kyōhō|Kyōhō 8]]) the shrine was granted the {{illm|first rank|ja|正一位}} in Japan's {{illm|Shinto Shrine ranking system|ja|神階}}{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} and the shrine's deity was given the [[shingō (Shinto)|title]] (<small>[[:ja:神 (神道)#「ミコト」（神号）|ja]]</small>) Kakinomoto Dai-myōjin (柿本大明神).{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}

== Name ==
The shrine is familiarly referred to by local people with the nickname ''Hitomaru-san'' (人丸さん).{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}

== Monuments and architecture ==
In the shrine grounds is a monument constructed on the order of {{illm|Matsudaira Nobuyuki|ja|松平信之}},{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}} inscribed with a 1,712-character biography of Hitomaro.{{sfn|Akashi Tourism Association|2017}}

